      "\n  sorry\n```\n\nThe goal at this point is to show `∑ x ∈ {x ∈ s | x ∈ s}.attach, w ⟨↑x, ...⟩ = ∑ i, w i`.\nThe `simp only` line simplifies `{x ∈ s | x ∈ s}.attach` to `↑s` (the coercion of the `Finset` `s` to a `Set`).\nSo the goal becomes `∑ x ∈ ↑s, w ⟨↑x, ...⟩ = ∑ i, w i`.\n\nThe `convert hw using 1` line attempts to rewrite the goal using `hw : ∑ i, w i = 1`.\nIf we rewrite `∑ i, w i` in the goal with `1`, the goal becomes `∑ x ∈ ↑s, w ⟨↑x, ...⟩ = 1`.\n\nThe `sorry` is because we haven't proven `∑ x ∈ ↑s, w ⟨↑x, ...⟩ = 1`.\nThe `fun i ↦ if hi : i ∈ s then w ⟨i, hi⟩ else 0` defines a function `f : ι → k`.\nThe `∑ i ∈ s, w i = 1` condition (`hw`) is about `w`.\nWe need to show `∑ x ∈ ↑s, f x = 1`.\n\nLet's trace the sum:\n`∑ x ∈ ↑s, w ⟨↑x, ...⟩` is a sum over a `Set`.\nThe `Finset` `s` is `{x | x ∈ s}` (the predicate is redundant).\nThe sum becomes `∑ i ∈ s, w i`.\nThis is exactly `hw`. So the goal `∑ x ∈ ↑s, w ⟨↑x, ...⟩ = 1` is true by `hw`.\n\nThe `simp only` line simplified the wrong thing.\nInstead of simplifying `{x ∈ s | x ∈ s}.attach` to `↑s`, we should be summing over `s` directly.\nThe expression `fun i ↦ if hi : i ∈ s then w ⟨i, hi⟩ else 0` is meant to be `w` restricted to `s`.\nLet's define `w' : {x | x ∈ s} → k := fun i ↦ w i`.\nThen `∑ x ∈ {x | x ∈ s}, w' x = hw`.\nThe sum `∑ x ∈ {x ∈ s | x ∈ s}.attach, w ⟨↑x, ...⟩` is `∑ x ∈ {x | x ∈ s}, w x`.\nThis is `hw`.\nSo the goal `∑ x ∈ {x ∈ s | x ∈ s}.attach, w ⟨↑x, ...⟩ = ∑ i, w i` is `hw = hw`. This is true.\n\nThe proof should be:\n```tactics\nrefine ⟨fun i ↦ if hi : i ∈ s then w ⟨i, hi⟩ else 0, ?_, ?_⟩\n· -- Show that ∑ i in s, (fun i ↦ if hi : i ∈ s then w ⟨i, hi⟩ else 0) i = 1\n  have h1 : ∑ i in s, (fun i ↦ if hi : i ∈ s then w ⟨i, hi⟩ else 0) i = ∑ i in s, w ⟨i, hi⟩ := by\n    apply Finset.sum_congr rfl\n    intro i hi\n    simp at hi ⊢\n    all_goals try tauto\n  rw [h1]\n  exact hw\n```\n\nWait, the sum is not over `s`. It's over `{x ∈ s | x ∈ s}.attach`.\nLet's look at the structure.\n`hp`